  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 5:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἥψατο",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": this also in all three—a cardinal point; the touch the practical proof of the will and the sympathy. No shrinking from the loathsome disease.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἡ λέπρα ἀπῆλθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": Lk. takes one of Mk.’s two phrases, Mt. the other. Lk. takes the one which most clearly implies a cure; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκαθερίσθη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Mt.) might conceivably mean: became technically clean.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and touched him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This was a distinct violation of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "letter",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but not of course of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "spirit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the Mosaic law (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 13:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In order to prevent the accidental violation of this law, lepers, until the final stage of the disease, were then as now secluded from all living contact with others, “differing in nothing from a dead man” (Jos. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " iii. 11 § 3), and only appeared in public with the cry ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Tamê, Tamê",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—‘Unclean! Unclean!’ But Jesus, “because He is the Lord of the Law, does not obey the Law, but makes the Law” (St Ambrose); or rather, he obeys that divine eternal Law of Compassion, in its sudden impulse (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "σπλαγχνισθεὶς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 1:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which is older and grander than the written Law. (So Elijah and Elisha had not scrupled to touch the dead, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 17:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 4:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) His touching the leper, yet remaining clean, is a type of His taking our humanity upon Him, remaining undefiled.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I will: be thou clean",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Two words in the original—“a prompt echo to the ripe faith of the leper”—which are accurately preserved by all three Evangelists. Our Lord’s first miracles were done with a glad spontaneity in answer to faith. But when men had ceased to believe in Him, then lack of faith rendered His later miracles more sad and more delayed (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:58",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). We never however hear of a moment s delay in attending to the cry of a leper. When the sinner cries from his heart, “I have sinned against the Lord,” the answer comes instantly, “The Lord also hath put away thy sin” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the leprosy departed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Jesus was not polluted by the touch, but the leper was cleansed. Even so he touched our sinful nature, yet without sin (H. de St Victore).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
